<!--Blackberry jam presentation-->
<body>
<div id="Presentation">
  <div>
<h1>Presentation</h1>
<p>I love to relax in the fall in the fields, walking with the
 baskets to pick blackberries. 
 For me it is a way to disconnect from the busy life and daily routine. But it is also one of my favorites, the jam with different extra flavors, pleasantly flavored with a stick of vanilla, 
along with a tea with bread spread with this jam. This jam is great!</p>
  </div>
</div>
<!--END Blackberry jam presentation-->

<!--Ingredients-->
<div id="Ingredients">
<ul>
<h1>Ingredients</h1>
<h3>
<li>1 kg blackberries</li>
<li>900 g of sugar</li>
<li>1 small lemon</li>
<li>1 vanilla pod or mint</li>
</h3>
</ul>
</div>
<!--END Ingredients-->

<!--Cooking steps-->
<div id="Cooking steps">
<h1>Cooking steps</h1>
<p>Wash the blackberries under a stream of cold water and then drain them
 very well. We put them in a saucepan with a thick bottom,
 adding the sugar will melt and leave a juice, 
and with the help of a spoon, we mix and partially crush them.</p>
<p>We put the pan on very low heat, mix well,
and add vanilla notched lengthwise.
 When the sugar starts to melt (after about 10 minutes),
add the juice of a small lemon.
The jam will start bubbling and leave more juice, 
then we can turn off the fire and let it become more juicy and rest for a few 
hours. After resting, put the jam back on low heat and boil it for about 30 or 
45 minutes, depending on how thick you want it. During boiling, we regularly 
remove the foam formed on the surface of the jam.</p>
<p>To check if the blackberry jam is ready, let the jam flow onto the cold plate 
and wait for the jam to cool down as well. If the syrup is bound after cooling
and consistent, then the boiling can be stopped.
We put it hot in the jars and then turn them upside down. 
When the jam is cold, we store the jars for the winter.</p>
</div>
<!--END Cooking steps-->

